title: Woman’s brother abandons kids at a young age, woman defends them when they don’t want to reconnect with him and new wife: ‘[They] had no business putting their mistakes on the girls.’
description: When you come from a family with a lot of grief and strife, there's often a ton of finger-pointing and random blaming. Some people can't own up to their own misgivings, so they try to make up a story to explain their actions without them being at fault. Other times, people are ready to come clean about their actions, but the hurt is too far embedded that no apology could revoke the damage done. There are also a lot of complicated feelings caught up in family drama. You love them all in a way you can't explain because they're family and they're yours, but also, you know them better than anyone and have no fear telling them that they're wrong. Or at least that you think they're wrong.Whatever the case, every family has drama and trauma that is unique to them and would be hard to explain to anyone who can't understand your family dynamics. Still, it helps to ask an outside opinion to explain the actions of the ones we love. One woman posted to Reddit searching for advice for her family troubles. Her brother wants to come back into the lives of his two daughters, whom he abandoned at a young age, and they don't want him back in their lives. This woman takes her niece's side, but she's wondering if she's being too harsh on her brother. What do you think?
author: Baiz Hoen

title: CEO demands employee work from office after a 2-second cameo of his 5-year-old daughter on a call, leads to his resignation: ‘She stood up and looked over my shoulder. She didn't make any noise’
description: Remember when we thought remote work would solve all our problems? No more commutes, no more office politics, just peaceful productivity in our pajamas. Oh, sweet summer children, how naive we were! While working from home has liberated us from fluorescent lighting and mysterious break room odors, it's created an entirely new circus of corporate absurdities.We're all living in this bizarre new world where our homes have become fishbowls, broadcasted to colleagues through the unforgiving eye of webcams. Suddenly, everyone's a critic of your bookshelves, your choice of virtual background, or just exposed to that questionable art piece your mother-in-law gifted you that's now visible unfortunately.Some companies have apparently developed policies more complex than international trade agreements about what can and cannot appear in your sacred two-foot-square Zoom rectangle, Or the unwritten rules about what constitutes a "professional" home office environment.Which leads me to today's story corporate acrobat: a dedicated employee who committed the unthinkable crime of allowing his five-year-old daughter to briefly exist in the same space as a late-night video call.
author: Etai Eshet

title: Bride stops wedding on her big day to rescue four stray kittens near the ceremony, she adopts them all on the happiest day of her life
description: Ah, mawwiage. Mawwiage is what brings us togevver, today (this is a Princess Bride reference for all of you clueless as to why we are horribly misspelling 'marriage'). But really though, marriage is a beautiful thing. It's the happiest day of your life, hopefully. It's also a very stressful day. For those of you who are married, you know the craziness that comes on your wedding day. You have a schedule that's packed tighter than a cat in a purrito, there is no margin for error and no time for any distractions.That is, unless, the cat distribution system knocks on your door. Imagine you're getting ready, your hair and makeup are done, you take your two-minute and 30-second break in the schedule to walk around and get some fresh air….and then you hear some meowing. Not just one meow, but four, eight, sixteen meows! Naturally, you investigate. You find four kittens in the venue, so what else can you do except put your wedding on hold and rescue the smol little babies? That's exactly what happened below, so scroll down to watch the whole heartwarming video!
author: Blake Seidel

title: 24 Orange Cat Memes With 0 Brain Cells and 1,000 Silly on the Hooman Humor Meter
description: Are you a pawrent of an orange cat? If you are, on the one hand - you have less to worry about, because you have the cat but minus the brain. So, technically, it's less to worry about, because it's literally less of a thing in the cat. But on the other hand, the fact your orange buddy has yet to obtain the single brain cell all orange cats share creates other things you should worry about. Like the orange cat behavior. And yes, we're 200% sure that if you're an orange cat pawrent you know exactly what sort of behavior we're talking about. The orange kind.For everyone else who does not pawrent an orange feline friend, let us demonstrate it to you with the power of memes. We gathered some cat memes that demonstrate the power of a 0 brain cell orange cat to create silly chaos all around them. But it's not just the chaos, it's the… orangeness. And it's definitely great for meme material. It's no wonder this genre of cat memes is flourishing.
author: Ayala Sorotsky

title: Error'd: Office Politics
description: "Math is hard, especially timely math," explains The Beast in Black.   Cinephile Jono enjoys contemporary dramas far more than sci-fi. "Letterboxd tells me I've logged this movie 3 times, I'm not sure I'll be watching it in 2566." I hope you are, Jono.   Pieter may have to turn in his official pedants card. Pieter is concerned about the apparent contradiction between the two salaries on offer here, declaring: "The title says She can earn up to 8.000 euro/month. But by the time you get to the actual article link, that amount deflated to 6.000 euro/month. I didn't know it was that bad in the euro zone! Or is it good, since we've got inflation under control? I don't know which way is up anymore..."Pieter, 6,000 is "up to" 8,000. Technically.   Cross-country runner Andrei looks to be taking the long way around for this trip. Says he, "According to Google Maps, one of my transfers involves teleporting about 70 km away to catch my next train."   Finally David B. reports "My wife works as a quality auditor for Initech [ed: the William Lumberg company, presumably, not the Flavor and Fragrance company]. When setting up contact information for a company she will be auditing in the near future they needed some basic information. So much for gender equality."
